title: [Web] InferenceSession.dispose method is not exposed

labels.name: platform:web
labels.description: issues related to ONNX Runtime web; typically submitted using template

body:
### Describe the issue

ONNXRuntime WASM backend will create native resources in WASM memory every time an InferenceSession is created. These resources are addessed by sessionId and retained until explicitly disposed by the user, but the `dispose` method is not exposed on InferenceSession, so it is not possible to actually dispose of InferenceSession properly and release memory.


### To reproduce

See above. The `dispose` method is present in OnnxruntimeWebAssemblyBackend but not in InferenceSession or InferenceSessionImpl. Memory release is not possible.

### Urgency

This affects long running web processes - such as browser extensions - that want to periodically update a model by creating a new InferenceSession. Eventually they run out of memory and session creation fails.
It is possible to work around the issue by overriding TypeScript and calling `session.handler.dispose()`, but this is a hack that uses undocumented APIs, so I'd rather not do that.

title: [Web] ONNX Runtime throws undescriptive exception

labels.name: platform:web
labels.description: issues related to ONNX Runtime web; typically submitted using template

body:
### Describe the issue

In the default configuration published to NPM, ONNX Runtime is compiled without exception support in emscripten, but it still makes heavy of use of C++ exceptions. As a result, it still calls into emscripten C++ exception code, which is stubbed out, and throws the C++ exception pointer as a JS exception (without even wrapping it into a WebAssembly.Exception or JS Error).
The C++ exception pointer appears a bare number, and it lacks context (stack) or even an error message, so it is essentially useless to debug what is going wrong.

I think ONNX Runtime should either compile with emscripten exceptions enabled (given it makes use of C++ exceptions), or it should disable C++ exceptions completely, and report errors in a different way that preserves error message.
Compiling with native WASM exceptions would be best, as it gives best performance and best observability. It is supported by all recent browsers: https://webassembly.org/roadmap/

### To reproduce

There are different ways to trigger C++ exceptions, and I don't know all of them (if I did, I could guard against all of them, and avoid this issue entirely). One way I know of is to pass an input that is too large for the model, which triggers a C++ exception in BroadcastIterator. Another way is to run out of WASM memory, which causes std::bad_alloc.

### Urgency

This issue makes it very hard to deploy ONNX Runtime in production, because without observability if errors occur one is stuck with no debugging options, but the alternative is to deploy a custom debug build, which does not seem appropriate for production.

title: Add Pre- and Post-tunning API to allow pre- and postprocessing of params
body:
This allows TunableOp to have accumulated inplace update to its buffer. So that we can finally implement GemmTunableOp correctly if `beta != 0`. That is, We need to create a proxy `params` for the tuning process. Otherwise, say, we tune it for `n` iterations, then during tuning $C^{(1)} = alpha A B + beta C^{(0)}$, ..., $C^{(n)} = alpha A B + beta C^{(n-1)}$. And for the actual run after tuning, the result will be $C^{(n+1)}$, whereas what we want is $C^{(1)}$. This only happens if the tuning's `FindFastest` is invoked.

This does not enable GEMM comming from CK to correctly support `alpha != 1` and `beta != 0`. To achieve it, we need to extend `GetCKGemmTypeStringAndOps` for it.

title: [CPU EP]optimize resize
body:
### Description
To simply the formula of bilinear-resize to save workload.

**Current imp in CPU EP**

$$
\begin{equation}
f(x,y) = (x2-x)(y2-y)\times f(q_{11}) -(x1-x)(y2-y)\times f(q_{21})+(x2-x)(y-y1)\times f(q_{12})-(x1-x)(y-y1)\times f(q_{22})
\end{equation} 
$$

There are 8 multiplications and 11 additions

**A more efficient one**

$$
\begin{align*}
f(r_1) &= \frac{x2-x}{x2-x1}\times f(q_{11}) +\frac{x-x1}{x2-x1}\times f(q_{21})  \\
&=\frac{x2-x}{x2-x1}\times (f(q_11)-f(q_21))  +f(q_21) \\
&=(x2-x)\times (f(q_11)-f(q_21)) +f(q_21) \\
\end{align*}
$$

$$
\begin{align*}
f(r_2) &= \frac{x2-x}{x2-x1}\times f(q_{12}) +\frac{x-x1}{x2-x1}\times f(q_{22})  \\
&=\frac{x2-x}{x2-x1}\times (f(q_12)-f(q_22))  +f(q_22) \\
&=(x2-x)\times (f(q_12)-f(q_22)) +f(q_22) \\
\end{align*}
$$

$$
\begin{align*}
f(x, y) &= \frac{y2-y}{y2-y1}\times f(r_1) +\frac{y-y1}{y2-y1}\times f(r_2)  \\
&=\frac{y2-y}{y2-y1}\times (f(r_1)-f(r_2))  +f(r_2) \\
&=(y2-y)\times (f(r_1)-f(r_2)) +f(r_2) \\
\end{align*}
$$

we have 3 multiplications and 9 additions in total.

title: Arena on GPU throw Segmentation fault in C++
body:
I followed the steps below, but onnxruntime gave the message and then exit with segmentation falut:
[F:onnxruntime:, bfc_arena.h:330 RegionFor] Could not find Region for 0x7ffb2b04d000

---

       Thanks @Z-XQ for the explanation.

The GPU memory is backed by a memory pool (arena) and we have a config knob to shrink the arena (de-allocated unused memory chunks). 

Not sure if we have enough tools to accomplish this in Python just yet. The best way to use this feature in C++ is to:

1) Not allocate weights memory through the arena: See [here](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/651955d3c91be9a1cbb3ce29360758c8347016ad/onnxruntime/test/shared_lib/test_inference.cc#L1731)


2) Configure the arena to have high enough initial chunk to support most Run() calls. See "initial_chunk_size_bytes" [here](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/651955d3c91be9a1cbb3ce29360758c8347016ad/onnxruntime/test/shared_lib/test_inference.cc#L1758)

3) Finally, configure the arena to shrink on every Run(). See [here](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/651955d3c91be9a1cbb3ce29360758c8347016ad/onnxruntime/test/shared_lib/test_inference.cc#L1777). This will keep the initial chunk allocated but de-allocate any unused chunk remaining after the Run() call ends.

For example, if the initial chunk size is set as 500MB, the first Run() will allocate 500MB + any additional chunks required to service the Run() call. The additional chunks will get de-allocated after Run() and only keep 500MB of memory allocated.  It is important to not allocate weights (initializers) memory through the arena as that complicates the shrinkage. Hence, step (1).

_Originally posted by @hariharans29 in https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/9509#issuecomment-951546580_

body:
### fix nightly ci failure
<!-- Describe your changes. -->

Our nightly CI (https://dev.azure.com/onnxruntime/onnxruntime/_build?definitionId=198&_a=summary) fail for few days. 

An example:

```
FAILED onnxruntime_src/orttraining_test_ortmodule_api.py::test_gradient_correctness_conv1d[EXHAUSTIVE-False-False]

        provider_options = ort_model._torch_module._execution_manager(
            ort_model._is_training()
        )._execution_agent._inference_session._provider_options
    
        expected_conv_algo_search = "HEURISTIC" if conv_algo_search is None else conv_algo_search
        actual_conv_algo_search = None
        if "CUDAExecutionProvider" in provider_options:
            actual_conv_algo_search = provider_options["CUDAExecutionProvider"]["cudnn_conv_algo_search"]
        elif "ROCMExecutionProvider" in provider_options:
            actual_conv_algo_search = provider_options["ROCMExecutionProvider"]["cudnn_conv_algo_search"]
```

### Describe the issue

Hey everybody, I'm using ORT with the C++ API to run a CPU inference on a model. I implemented a class that creates an inference session in its constructor taking a static Ort::Env env and default Ort::SessionOptions. It also has a method that calls Ort::Sesion Run() on the session.

title: oneDNN ep bf16 enabling
body:
### Description
 This adds bfloat16 support to the oneDNN ep.

When using the oneDNN ep this enables bfloat16 support for the following ops:

Exp, Sigmoid, Tanh, Relu, MatMul, Gelu, BiasGelu, Add, Sub,
Mul, Div, Div, Sqrt, Pow, ReduceMean,  Abs, Cast, Equal, Exp,
FastGelu, FusedMatMul, Gemm, Greter, GreaterOrEqual, LeakyRelu,
Less, LessOrEqual, LRN, ReduceOps, Reshape, Squeeze, Transpose,
 and Unsqueeze.

LayerNorm with some internal casting. 
BatchNorm only enabled BFloat16 for input and output, scale and bias still need fp32 input.

Added bfloat16 unit tests for all of the operators in question. When possible we reused the already existing unit tests that were added by CUDA and ROCM eps.

In many of the unit tests an unusual pattern will be seen 

    #if defined(USE_DNNL)
    TEST(Test, bfloat16_test) {
      #if defined(USE_DNNL)
        // oneDNN ep specific code
      #endif
       //test code
    }
    #endif

Although it looks unusual this was purposely done if another ep implements bfloat16 support for that operator they will be able to enable the unit test by adding there execution provider to the first line without needing to edit inside the test.

Example: `#if defined(USE_CUDA) || defined(USE_DNNL)`  see the MatMul_float16 test in matmul_test.cc for and example of how this is useful.

Additionally two new ISA checks (AVX512_BF16 and AMX-BF16) were added to the cpuid_info code in.  This was important to detecting is bfloat16 operations are supported by the CPU.

### Motivation and Context
This expands the capabilities of the oneDNN execution provider to support models containing bfloat16 operations.
